The Order offers a modern, professional insurance operation with more than $100 billion of life insurance policies in force and $19.8 billion in assets as of June 2013[update],[70] a figure more than double the 2000 levels.[57][70] Nearly 80,000 life certificates were issued in 2013, almost 30,000 more than the Order's closest competitor, to bring the total to 1.73 million.[57] The program has a $1.8 billion surplus.[57]
Over $286 million in death benefits were paid in 2012 and $1.7 billion were paid between 2000 and 2010.[57] This is large enough to rank 49th on the A. M. Best list of all life insurance companies in North America.[71] Since the founding of the Order, $3.5 billion in death benefits have been paid.[72] Premiums in 2012 were nearly $1.2 billion, and dividends paid out totaled more than $274 million.[57] Over the same time period, annuity deposits rose 4.2%, compared to an 8% loss for the industry as a whole.[57]
Every day in 2012 more than $10 million was invested, for a total of $2.7 billion on the year, and an annual income of $905 million.[57] The Order maintains a two prong investment strategy. A company must first be a sound investment before stock in it is purchased, and secondly the company's activities must not conflict with Catholic social teaching.[57] The Order also provides mortgages to churches and Catholic schools at "very competitive rates" through its ChurchLoan program.[57]
Products include permanent and term life insurance, as well as annuities, long term care insurance, and disability insurance.[70] The insurance program is not a separate business offered by the Order to others but is exclusively for the benefit of members and their families.[73] According to the Fortune 1000 list, the Knights of Columbus ranked 900 in total revenue in 2011[74] and, with more than 1,500 agents, was 925th in size in 2015.[57] All agents are members of the Order.[citation needed]
The Order's insurance program is the most highly rated program in North America.[57] For 40 consecutive years, the Order has received A. M. Best's highest rating, A++.[57][75] Additionally, the Order is certified by the Insurance Marketplace Standards Association for ethical sales practices.[9] Standard & Poor's downgraded the insurance program's financial strength/credit rating from AAA to AA+ in August 2011 not due to the Order's financial strength, but due to its lowering of the long-term sovereign credit rating of the United States to AA+.[76][77][nb 1] Additionally, the insurance program has a low 3.5% lapse rate of the 1.9 million members and their families who are insured.[57][70]
