^ "Columbian Squires". Knights of Columbus. Archived from the original on June 9, 2013. Retrieved June 28, 2013. 
^ "Squires Membership". Knights of Columbus. Archived from the original on July 2, 2013. Retrieved June 28, 2013. 
^ Kolyer, Alex (May 7, 2012). "Photos: Catholics march from Capitol to Cathedral in support of marriage amendment". Minnesota Public Radio. Retrieved November 4, 2013. 
^ "Squire Roses Circle". Knights of Columbus Council 5561. Archived from the original on May 23, 2013. Retrieved June 28, 2013. 
^ Kaufmann, Eric P. (May 17, 2007). The Orange Order: A Contemporary Northern Irish History. Oxford University Press. p. 315. ISBN 9780199208487. Likwise with joint Orange-Knights of Columbus functions: the two organizations share a common experience of trying to survive in a difficult social environment. 
^ Marchildon, Gregory P. (2009). Immigration and Settlement, 1870-1939. University of Regina Press. p. 8. ISBN 9780889772304. Irish Catholics responded to the Orange Order with their own society, the Knights of Columbus. 


